====Suffix====
{{ja-pos|suffix}}

# [[seem]]ing that, seeming like, [[appear]]ing that

=====Usage notes=====
This productive suffix meaning “seeming like” can come after a full phrase in plain form, or after a verb or adjective stem, thereby forming a ''-na'' adjective.

* After a full phrase in plain form, the resulting phrase implies reported speech, something heard from someone else. For example, the verb {{m|ja|降る|tr=furu|t=to fall from the sky}} plus this suffix forms {{m|ja||降る'''そう'''|tr=furu '''sō'''|t='''I've heard that''' it will rain” or “'''someone told me that''' it will rain}}. The adjective {{m|ja|美味しい|tr=oishii|t=delicious}} plus this suffix forms {{m|ja||美味しい'''そう'''|tr=oishii '''sō'''|t='''I've heard that''' it's delicious}}.

* After a verb or adjective stem, the resulting word means “it looks like X”. For example, the stem {{m|ja||降り|tr=furi-}} of the verb {{m|ja|降る|tr=furu|t=to fall from the sky}} plus this suffix forms {{m|ja||降り'''そう'''|tr=furi'''sō'''|t=it '''looks''' like it will rain}}. The stem {{m|ja||美味し|tr=oishi-}} of the adjective {{m|ja|美味しい|tr=oishii|t=delicious}} plus this suffix forms {{m|ja||美味し'''そう'''|tr=oishi'''sō'''|t='''looks''' delicious}}. However, {{m|ja|良い|いい|tr=ii}} + {{m|ja||そう}} becomes {{m|ja|よさそう|tr=yosasō}} and {{m|ja|ない|tr=nai}} + {{m|ja||そう}} becomes {{m|ja|なさそう|tr=nasasō}}.

The suffix should not be used after stem forms describing visually obvious physical traits like color. Although {{m|ja||赤い'''そう'''|tr=akai '''sō'''|t='''I've heard that''' it's red}} would be valid, {{m|ja||*赤'''そう'''|tr=aka'''sō'''|t=it '''seems''' red}} would not. Another example of this is that {{m|ja|可愛い|tr=kawaii}} means someone looks cute so it does not need another {{m|ja||そう}}. ({{m|ja|かわいそう|tr=kawaisō}} does exist, but means “pitiful” or “poor”.) The suffix should, however, be used when describing another person's mood or mental state. For example, if another person looks glad, one says {{m|ja||嬉し'''そう'''|tr=ureshi'''sō'''|t=you '''seem''' glad}}, which is more natural and polite than saying {{m|ja|嬉しい|tr=ureshii|t=you are glad}}.

This word is morphologically a [[clitic]] after a phrase in plain form, and an [[inflectional]] [[suffix]] after a verb or adjective stem. It is classified as a {{m|ja|助動詞|tr=jodōshi|t=auxiliary verb}} in traditional Japanese grammar.

